%N A120427 For each y >= 1 there are only finitely many values of x >= 1 such that x-y and x+y are both squares; list all such pairs (x,y) with gcd(x,y) = 1 ordered by values of y; sequence gives y values.
%C A120427 Ordered even legs of primitive Pythagorean triangles.
%C A120427 I wrote an arithmetic program once to find out if and when y 'catches up to' n in A120427 (ordered even legs of primitive Pythagorean triples). It's around 16700. As enumerated by the even - or odd - legs, (not sure about the hypotenuses), the triples are 'denser' than the integers. - Stephen Waldman, Jun 12 2007
%C A120427 Conjecture: lim_{n->oo} a(n)/n = 1/Pi. - _Lothar Selle_, Jun 19 2022
%D A120427 Lothar Selle, Kleines Handbuch Pythagoreische Zahlentripel, Books on Demand, 3rd impression 2022, chapter 2.3.1.
%D A120427 Donald D. Spencer, Computers in Number Theory, Computer Science Press, Rockville MD, 1982, pp. 130-131.
%H A120427 D. N. Lehmer, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2369728">Asymptotic evaluation of certain totient sums</a>, Amer. J. Math. 22, 293-335, 1900.
%F A120427 The solutions are given by x = r^2 + 2*r*k + 2*k^2, y = 2*k*(k+r) with r >= 1, k >= 1, r odd, gcd(r, k) = 1.
%F A120427 a(n) = 2*A020887(n) = 4*A020888(n).
%e A120427 Pairs are [5, 4], [17, 8], [13, 12], [37, 12], [65, 16], [29, 20], [101, 20], ... E.g., 5-4 = 1^2, 5+4 = 3^2.
